<section xml:id="section-assignment1">
  <title>Assignment 1</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Evaluate the following integrals. You don't need to show all
        the steps of the individual single integrals, but make sure
        the steps to setup and work through the iterated integral are
        clealry shown and explained. (12) 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><me>
          \int_{[0,1] \times [0,1]} (x^3 + y^3 - (xy)^2) dA 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int_{[0,3] \times [0,2]} \frac{xy^2}{x^2+4} dA 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int_{[0,1] \times [0,\pi]} x \sec^2 (xy) dA 
        </me></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Evaluate the following integrals. You may need to switch the
        order of integration. Describe the region of integration
        (either in words or by drawing). As before, show all the setup
        work but you don't need to show all the steps of the single
        variable integration. (16) 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><me>
          \int_0^2 \int_0^{4-y^2} \frac{2}{\sqrt{4-y^2}} dx dy 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int_0^1 \int_0^{1-y^2} (x+y) dx dy 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int_0^1 \int_y^1 \sin (\pi x^2) dx xy 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \int_0^2 \int_{y^2}^4 \sqrt{x} \sin (\pi x) dx dy   
        </me></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the areas between each set of two loci. (8) 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><me>
          y = -x^2 \text{ and } 3x + y = 2 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          xy = 3 \text{ and } x^2 + y^2 = 10 
        </me></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the volume of the tetrahedron with vertices
        <m>(0,0,0</m>, <m>(0,0,3)</m>, <m>(0,2,0</m> and
        <m>(0,0,1</m>. (6) 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be two piecewise continuous
        functions defined on <m>I = [0,1] \times [0,1]</m>. Assume
        that <m>f = g</m> everywhere except on the line <m>x=y</m>.
        Using the Riemann definition of the integral, argue that the
        following equality must be true. (4) 
        <me>
          \int_I f dA = \int_I g dA
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
